{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6796318c-a631-4ee3-a399-06be8328a467","content":"Your sample file actually compiles fine because both sides are already typed as `object`, so the compiler infers `Assert.AreEqual<object>`. The CS1503 error occurs when types are **mixed** — e.g., `Assert.AreEqual(\"hello\", someObject)` where one arg is `string` and the other is `object`.\n\n**MSTest v3 removed** the non-generic `Assert.AreEqual(object, object)`. Only the generic `Assert.AreEqual<T>(T, T)` remains, so the compiler must unify both arguments to one `T`.\n\n**Fix:** Add an explicit type parameter:\n\n```csharp\n// Before (fails when types mismatch):\nAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual);\n\n// After:\nAssert.AreEqual<object>(expected, actual);\n```\n\nThis tells the compiler to use `T = object`, matching the old v2 behavior. Apply the same pattern to `AreNotEqual<object>(...)` if needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0dd6c4b0-03c2-4615-ab21-1f66969903a9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Interesting - the build succeeded. Let me check the MSTest version more carefully. The code actually compiles because `Assert.AreEqual<object>(object, object)` still works when both arguments are typed as `object`. The CS1503 error the user describes typically happens when you have mixed types, like `Assert.AreEqual(someString, someObject)` where the compiler can't unify the generic type parameter.\n\nBut the user is asking about this pattern in general. Let me explain the issue and the fix.\n\nActually, the build succeeded because both `expected` and `actual` are already typed as `object`, so the generic `Assert.AreEqual<T>(T, T)` resolves to `Assert.AreEqual<object>(object, object)`. The CS1503 error happens when you have something like `Assert.AreEqual(\"hello\", someObject)` where one arg is `string` and the other is `object` - the compiler can't pick between `T=string` and `T=object`.\n\n\nSince the user mentioned getting errors, their actual code probably has mismatched types that the sample doesn't show. The fix is to either explicitly specify the generic type like `Assert.AreEqual<object>(expected, actual)` or cast the arguments to match. The real problem in MSTest v3 is that the non-generic overload was removed, forcing you to be explicit about types when they don't naturally align.","outputTokens":730},"id":"c186a267-1f9e-4902-95cb-663ca10b4f72","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:05:47.130Z","parentId":"2991af77-8b95-41e3-bab5-19e786f3d872"}
